00:51:27,918 --> 00:51:33,301
was we wanted to save the reveal of the foul presence being

933
00:51:33,301 --> 00:51:37,803
a part of this fight and have it be a little bit of a surprise

934
00:51:37,803 --> 00:51:40,004
still while still retaining that something's

935
00:51:40,004 --> 00:51:43,186
wrong with Quo Lock vibe that we had in the previous animation.

936
00:51:43,186 --> 00:51:46,728
And here we also decided to lean more into the fact

937
00:51:46,728 --> 00:51:48,869
that he's a toad and use the tongue rather than

938
00:51:48,869 --> 00:51:50,470
his little froggy hands and stuff.

939
00:51:51,028 --> 00:51:54,651
But as you can see here, now we show the player

940
00:51:54,651 --> 00:51:56,512
with this reveal with the tentacles

941
00:51:56,512 --> 00:52:00,435
that Kolok has become corrupted by this familiar face

942
00:52:00,435 --> 00:52:02,216
from earlier in the game.

943
00:52:02,216 --> 00:52:04,598
And this is where the player could maybe start to realize,

944
00:52:04,598 --> 00:52:06,920
had they not cleared the mill, this might not

945
00:52:06,920 --> 00:52:08,401
have happened to their friend.

946
00:52:08,401 --> 00:52:09,862
I'm a horrible person.

947
00:52:09,862 --> 00:52:11,903
But then also, he asked me to do it.

948
00:52:11,903 --> 00:52:13,925
So it was his own demise.

949
00:52:13,925 --> 00:52:17,968
Like, he was the architect of his own demise, pretty much.

950
00:52:17,968 --> 00:52:19,789
So there's a lot more layers to it now.

951
00:52:20,247 --> 00:52:23,868
that we've done the work to really make this land better.

952
00:52:23,868 --> 00:52:27,751
So then in the fight, obviously, we

953
00:52:27,751 --> 00:52:31,112
still want to have this touching reunion moment with him

954
00:52:31,112 --> 00:52:32,073
that lands emotionally.

955
00:52:32,073 --> 00:52:34,014
And that's not going to happen if he's just

956
00:52:34,014 --> 00:52:36,795
basically a monster for the rest of the time

957
00:52:36,795 --> 00:52:37,496
that we have with him.

958
00:52:37,496 --> 00:52:40,717
So at the end of the fight, we made this conscious decision

959
00:52:40,717 --> 00:52:42,358
that Pollock fights back.

960
00:52:42,358 --> 00:52:44,519
We do the final hit, and then he starts

961
00:52:44,519 --> 00:52:47,501
struggling against his captor and gets pulled off screen.

962
00:52:48,190 --> 00:52:53,534
And then from that point on, we need to sort of follow Kowlok up there and sort of see what the

963
00:52:53,534 --> 00:52:57,858
resolution is. We're concerned at this point, but we know that we've completed the fight,

964
00:52:57,858 --> 00:53:04,322
so all that's left is the resolution. And what we discover is that Kowlok basically overtook the

965
00:53:04,322 --> 00:53:11,968
Stink Spirit off screen, and he basically gets to finish that arc. He gets to have that last laugh,

966
00:53:11,968 --> 00:53:12,408
pretty much.

967
00:53:12,767 --> 00:53:17,269
And we found that that was very important for Koloch to have this little triumph of his own,

968
00:53:17,269 --> 00:53:22,112
as opposed to us killing the thing and just freeing him. So that way, you know, he fights

969
00:53:22,112 --> 00:53:27,395
back a little bit more and it feels more endearing for him as a character and everything he's been

970
00:53:27,395 --> 00:53:33,378
through pretty much. And then basically we wrap and we get the Wisp back as he sort of dies and

971
00:53:33,378 --> 00:53:40,182
fades away. We can continue our quest, but emotionally it really stings because we sort of

972
00:53:40,182 --> 00:53:42,503
paved the way for this moment to be able to happen.

973
00:53:44,240 --> 00:53:50,044
And then we completely undermined all that work by filling this path that the player goes back

974
00:53:50,044 --> 00:53:55,147
afterwards with enemies, because we were focused on, oh, we don't want a long, boring stretch

975
00:53:55,147 --> 00:54:00,751
filled with nothing to do. Let's put enemies in combat and things to keep you busy. But then

976
00:54:00,751 --> 00:54:03,493
we realized very quickly, seeing people play this,

977
00:54:03,856 --> 00:54:10,240
that it was a complete emotional whiplash because they were still completely taken by this emotional

978
00:54:10,240 --> 00:54:14,522
moment. Some of them were still crying at this point. We have this beautiful emotional music

979
00:54:14,522 --> 00:54:18,384
that our composer wrote and we completely undermined it by filling this path with

980
00:54:18,384 --> 00:54:22,927
dangerous things and enemies and stuff. And so similar to the silent woods, we stripped away

981
00:54:22,927 --> 00:54:28,851
all of those layers and we just let the emotional moment breathe and it was far more powerful as a

982
00:54:28,851 --> 00:54:29,291
result.

983
00:54:32,306 --> 00:54:36,888
So this final set of smaller case studies I want to share,

984
00:54:36,888 --> 00:54:39,349
it all has to do with that final point I kind of just

985
00:54:39,349 --> 00:54:42,730
mentioned with having breathing room, letting moments breathe,

986
00:54:42,730 --> 00:54:45,971
but just sort of like global pacing as well.

987
00:54:45,971 --> 00:54:49,173
Because we realize we design levels on a very micro flow

988
00:54:49,173 --> 00:54:52,214
level where everything has to be very tight and fun

989
00:54:52,214 --> 00:54:54,695
and challenging.

990
00:54:54,695 --> 00:54:57,876
But then when you start to put a lot of these micro flow chunks

991
00:54:57,876 --> 00:54:58,396
together.

992
00:54:58,897 --> 00:55:05,580
to make a world, suddenly the macro flow matters in a big way, and the way that you flow from one

993
00:55:05,580 --> 00:55:10,763
of those sections to another and the pacing between them becomes very significant. So for example,

994
00:55:10,763 --> 00:55:18,107
at the well spring, the water mill that I mentioned earlier, the room right before that big

995
00:55:18,107 --> 00:55:23,850
water escape sequence that we have with the foul presence used to look something like this,

996
00:55:23,850 --> 00:55:26,932
where it was this very tight, very spiky, maze-like

997
00:55:27,292 --> 00:55:29,913
challenge heavy environment, very oppressive.

998
00:55:29,913 --> 00:55:33,013
And honestly, it wasn't all that fun.

999
00:55:33,013 --> 00:55:35,694
And very late in production,

1000
00:55:35,694 --> 00:55:38,774
we finally got the okay to try breaking

1001
00:55:38,774 --> 00:55:41,415
this entire level apart, this room,

1002
00:55:41,415 --> 00:55:44,415
and doing something very different there.

1003
00:55:44,415 --> 00:55:46,095
And so we opted for was creating

1004
00:55:46,095 --> 00:55:48,236
an environmental storytelling space,

1005
00:55:48,236 --> 00:55:49,436
which served multiple purposes.

1006
00:55:49,436 --> 00:55:53,317
One, it was allowing us to actually give more insight

1007
00:55:53,317 --> 00:55:56,257
into the lore of the world through environmental storytelling.

1008
00:55:56,843 --> 00:55:59,365
but two, it also served as a pacing break

1009
00:55:59,365 --> 00:56:02,487
right before this very challenging escape sequence.

1010
00:56:02,487 --> 00:56:05,169
The player was already spending so much time

1011
00:56:05,169 --> 00:56:07,470
in challenge mode climbing up to this part

1012
00:56:07,470 --> 00:56:08,751
of the water mill.

1013
00:56:08,751 --> 00:56:11,072
They didn't need another room of challenge

1014
00:56:11,072 --> 00:56:12,813
right before another challenge.

1015
00:56:12,813 --> 00:56:13,614
They needed a break.

1016
00:56:13,614 --> 00:56:15,415
They needed to be able to relax a little bit,

1017
00:56:15,415 --> 00:56:18,677
soak in the environment and appreciate this place

1018
00:56:18,677 --> 00:56:21,538
that's been so oppressive to them up until this point.

1019
00:56:21,538 --> 00:56:23,940
And so we just let the artists and storytellers

1020
00:56:23,940 --> 00:56:25,701
go wild with a big empty room.

1021
00:56:26,112 --> 00:56:27,893
and make it whatever they felt was going

1022
00:56:27,893 --> 00:56:29,353
to be the most interesting.

1023
00:56:29,353 --> 00:56:33,074
And ultimately, it made for a much better experience

1024
00:56:33,074 --> 00:56:34,895
for the Wellspring as a whole.

1025
00:56:34,895 --> 00:56:40,756
Bar's Reach is another example where

1026
00:56:40,756 --> 00:56:42,597
we needed to pay attention to pacing

1027
00:56:42,597 --> 00:56:44,898
environmental storytelling and art as well.

1028
00:56:44,898 --> 00:56:48,979
Originally, Bar's Reach, it's our frosty peak environment

1029
00:56:48,979 --> 00:56:49,899
in the game.

1030
00:56:50,579 --> 00:56:52,620
snow peak themed pretty much.

1031
00:56:52,620 --> 00:56:54,901
And one of the gameplay elements we have in there

1032
00:56:54,901 --> 00:56:57,342
are these sort of cauldrons that you heat up

1033
00:56:57,342 --> 00:57:00,043
by flapping some air onto them like a bellows,

1034
00:57:00,043 --> 00:57:01,864
and then they shoot out a projectile.

1035
00:57:01,864 --> 00:57:03,705
So when this area was designed,

1036
00:57:03,705 --> 00:57:05,846
this was the entrance to Bar's Reach,

1037
00:57:05,846 --> 00:57:07,087
and it was designed purely

1038
00:57:07,087 --> 00:57:08,808
from a mechanical gameplay standpoint,

1039
00:57:08,808 --> 00:57:11,729
which is I'm introducing this gameplay element,

1040
00:57:11,729 --> 00:57:13,390
it's going to open the door.

1041
00:57:13,390 --> 00:57:15,451
I know that the player has understood the element

1042
00:57:15,451 --> 00:57:17,032
because they opened the door.

1043
00:57:17,032 --> 00:57:18,493
Cool, now let's go forward

1044
00:57:18,493 --> 00:57:20,033
and explore the rest of Bar's Reach.

1045
00:57:21,260 --> 00:57:24,440
The thing is, we had something far more interesting

1046
00:57:24,440 --> 00:57:26,581
that we could use to gate that area.

1047
00:57:26,581 --> 00:57:29,462
We had already done a prototype of Bar.

1048
00:57:29,462 --> 00:57:33,443
He's a large story NPC that I can't go into detail on right

1049
00:57:33,443 --> 00:57:33,783
now.

1050
00:57:33,783 --> 00:57:37,764
But he's significant for the game in a number of ways.

1051
00:57:37,764 --> 00:57:39,684
And we thought it would be fun to be

1052
00:57:39,684 --> 00:57:43,665
able to tickle his nose and have him sneeze and open up a path

1053
00:57:43,665 --> 00:57:45,045
pretty much to move forward.

1054
00:57:45,045 --> 00:57:48,106
But the thing is, when the designer was putting together

1055
00:57:48,106 --> 00:57:50,667
the environment, they didn't really

1056
00:57:51,078 --> 00:57:54,839
the novelty of that or the significance of having that in a prominent location.

1057
00:57:54,839 --> 00:57:58,480
So they placed it somewhere in the middle of the environment,

1058
00:57:58,480 --> 00:58:02,921
just sort of like to have it, but not really to use it properly, let's say.

1059
00:58:02,921 --> 00:58:07,743
And so then looking critically on the environment near the end of the project,

1060
00:58:07,743 --> 00:58:10,344
we realized that the artists needed more room to breathe.

1061
00:58:10,344 --> 00:58:12,584
They needed more room to transition.

1062
00:58:12,584 --> 00:58:15,505
And so what we did was we gave them more flat space

1063
00:58:15,505 --> 00:58:18,426
that they could use to sort of almost crossfade the environments.

1064
00:58:19,146 --> 00:58:24,611
into each other, and we also decided to replace that very gamey gating system with the cauldron

1065
00:58:24,611 --> 00:58:32,477
with this more interesting, memorable, striking bar gate that actually used the exact same input,

1066
00:58:32,477 --> 00:58:37,422
the same kind of gating, the same ability, just in a much more contextualized and interesting way.

1067
00:58:37,422 --> 00:58:41,865
And actually the fact that you can discover this gate so early in the game.

1068
00:58:42,320 --> 00:58:45,361
it adds this sense of wonder and mystery to the environment

1069
00:58:45,361 --> 00:58:48,482
because you discover this snoring giant bear in a cave

1070
00:58:48,482 --> 00:58:50,683
and you wonder what lies beyond,

1071
00:58:50,683 --> 00:58:53,364
but you can only discover it later on in act two of the game

1072
00:58:53,364 --> 00:58:54,885
when you have a new ability.

1073
00:58:54,885 --> 00:58:57,586
And so that was a much, much stronger gate

1074
00:58:57,586 --> 00:59:01,027
and a much better transition and build up

1075
00:59:01,027 --> 00:59:02,588
pretty much than what we had originally.

1076
00:59:05,138 --> 00:59:08,100
Our sort of dark, insect-infested environment,

1077
00:59:08,100 --> 00:59:11,002
called Moldwood Depths, it had a similar issue

1078
00:59:11,002 --> 00:59:14,185
where the entrance was this giant spider statue,

1079
00:59:14,185 --> 00:59:17,367
but it was gameplay-focused, covered in spikes.

1080
00:59:17,367 --> 00:59:20,249
Player has to do these sort of tricky maneuvers

1081
00:59:20,249 --> 00:59:22,711
to then unblock some random door.

1082
00:59:22,711 --> 00:59:26,374
It didn't really feel all that interesting or memorable,

1083
00:59:26,374 --> 00:59:27,515
pretty much.

1084
00:59:27,515 --> 00:59:30,778
And so while we had this nice transition zone,

1085
00:59:30,778 --> 00:59:32,619
certainly different from Bar, what we

1086
00:59:33,937 --> 00:59:36,519
was just really a better gate.

1087
00:59:36,519 --> 00:59:38,380
And so Jeremy did some paint overs

1088
00:59:38,380 --> 00:59:42,183
and suggested that we have just this giant spider statue

1089
00:59:42,183 --> 00:59:45,866
as purely an environmental landmark in the background.

1090
00:59:45,866 --> 00:59:47,987
And when we eventually have the ability

1091
00:59:47,987 --> 00:59:49,949
to come here in the story,

1092
00:59:49,949 --> 00:59:51,090
that we have some little friends

1093
00:59:51,090 --> 00:59:52,731
that come and unlock this big gate.

1094
00:59:53,172 --> 01:00:00,515
So we decided that the story was that the Moldwood Depths was sealed off years ago because it was so corrupted and infested,

1095
01:00:00,515 --> 01:00:04,896
but they're going to open it for us because the Wisp is down there and we need to find it, right?

1096
01:00:04,896 --> 01:00:10,058
And so what we ended up doing was leaning into this and created this sort of opening in the floor,

1097
01:00:10,058 --> 01:00:13,179
sort of to have that, to emphasize that feeling that you're going underground,

1098
01:00:13,179 --> 01:00:18,520
and then this sort of, you know, wind would bellow up when it opened and spores were coming out.

1099
01:00:18,520 --> 01:00:22,462
So it really feel like this place, this temple hasn't been opened in a very long time.

1100
01:00:23,100 --> 01:00:26,322
And again, similar to Bar, you can discover this statue

1101
01:00:26,322 --> 01:00:29,304
very early on in the game and have the sense of wonder

1102
01:00:29,304 --> 01:00:32,345
and wondering what's going to happen here eventually.

1103
01:00:32,345 --> 01:00:35,927
And when you come back and it actually does get unsealed,

1104
01:00:35,927 --> 01:00:37,108
it feels magical.

1105
01:00:37,108 --> 01:00:39,869
And again, we just put it, the design

1106
01:00:39,869 --> 01:00:42,431
took a backseat for environmental storytelling

1107
01:00:42,431 --> 01:00:44,132
and pacing, and it really paid off.

1108
01:00:44,132 --> 01:00:47,754
And the final example, I'm running low on time.

1109
01:00:48,722 --> 01:00:49,982
is the Wintorn Ruins.

1110
01:00:49,982 --> 01:00:52,442
So the Wintorn Ruins was meant to be

1111
01:00:52,442 --> 01:00:54,383
the final dungeon of the game,

1112
01:00:54,383 --> 01:00:57,224
a full dungeon just like the other ones that we had,

1113
01:00:57,224 --> 01:01:00,024
but due to production concerns and scope issues,

1114
01:01:00,024 --> 01:01:02,065
we decided to trim it down heavily.

1115
01:01:02,065 --> 01:01:04,125
But we still didn't want to give up on the fact

1116
01:01:04,125 --> 01:01:07,986
that it was meant to be a very tricky gameplay challenge

1117
01:01:07,986 --> 01:01:09,626
like everything else in the game.

1118
01:01:09,626 --> 01:01:11,367
And so we combined all these elements,

1119
01:01:11,367 --> 01:01:15,268
like darkness and explosions and lasers and spikes,

1120
01:01:15,268 --> 01:01:16,948
and people in the team hated it.

1121
01:01:16,948 --> 01:01:17,868
It really felt out of place.

1122
01:01:18,117 --> 01:01:19,498
And also because it was leading up

1123
01:01:19,498 --> 01:01:22,460
to the final escape sequence of the game, which is very, very

1124
01:01:22,460 --> 01:01:23,781
challenging in itself.

1125
01:01:23,781 --> 01:01:27,103
And similar to the well spring and the water mill,

1126
01:01:27,103 --> 01:01:30,305
leading up to the final challenge with a challenge,

1127
01:01:30,305 --> 01:01:32,506
pacing-wise, felt very inappropriate.

1128
01:01:32,506 --> 01:01:35,107
And so we decided to take a similar note from the well

1129
01:01:35,107 --> 01:01:38,249
spring and take this very linear section

1130
01:01:38,249 --> 01:01:40,431
that we streamlined it to and fill it

1131
01:01:40,431 --> 01:01:43,032
with sort of environmental storytelling,

1132
01:01:43,032 --> 01:01:46,174
beautiful frescoes that our art team put together.

1133
01:01:46,598 --> 01:01:48,159
And this also gave us an opportunity

1134
01:01:48,159 --> 01:01:51,742
to tell more about the history of the world of Ori

1135
01:01:51,742 --> 01:01:53,643
and the Will of the Wisps, and also

1136
01:01:53,643 --> 01:01:57,085
foreshadow the final conclusion and Ori's fate,

1137
01:01:57,085 --> 01:02:00,168
pretty much, in a very interesting and memorable way.

1138
01:02:00,168 --> 01:02:03,550
And ultimately, playing through this longer story sequence,

1139
01:02:03,550 --> 01:02:05,652
very linear, lacking in challenge,

1140
01:02:05,652 --> 01:02:09,915
all focused on story, it really ended up, pacing-wise,

1141
01:02:09,915 --> 01:02:12,317
being the best thing to create that sort of calm

1142
01:02:12,317 --> 01:02:13,177
before the storm.

1143
01:02:13,585 --> 01:02:16,988
right as you then approach that final escape sequence,

1144
01:02:16,988 --> 01:02:19,390
and then challenges you for a few hours, pretty much.

1145
01:02:19,390 --> 01:02:24,394
So just like with all of these examples,

1146
01:02:24,394 --> 01:02:26,835
ultimately, creating Ori and the Will of the Wisps

1147
01:02:26,835 --> 01:02:28,657
and making it the way that we made it,

1148
01:02:28,657 --> 01:02:31,719
it really ended up having to be a marriage of story,

1149
01:02:31,719 --> 01:02:32,580
and design, and art.

1150
01:02:32,580 --> 01:02:35,462
And we had to really compromise on all fronts

1151
01:02:35,462 --> 01:02:38,705
to kind of make that the best possible whole

1152
01:02:38,705 --> 01:02:40,806
that it could be so that this story resonated

1153
01:02:40,806 --> 01:02:42,928
with the players in the way that we wanted it to.

1154
01:02:44,152 --> 01:02:45,595
I appreciate your time.

1155
01:02:45,595 --> 01:02:47,859
Thanks on behalf of Jeremy and myself.

1156
01:02:47,859 --> 01:02:51,906
You can find more from both of us on our Twitters, basically.

1157
01:02:51,906 --> 01:02:54,510
And I hope you have a great GDC.

1158
01:02:54,510 --> 01:02:55,812
And thanks for listening.

1159
01:02:55,812 --> 01:02:58,196
Hope you learned something from our talk.

